{{short description|Withdrawal of labor by US teachers, 2018}} {{Infobox civil conflict |title= 2018 teachers' strikes in the United States |image= |caption= |date= February 23, 2018 – present |place=[[United States]] |causes= *Budget cuts *Decreased [[employee benefits]] *Low per pupil spending *Low salaries *[[Right-to-work law]] *[[School choice]] *[[School voucher]]s |goals= |notes= |methods= *[[Civil resistance]] *[[Demonstration (protest)|Demonstrations]] *[[Strike action]]s *[[Internet activism]] *[[Silent protest]]s *[[Sit-in]]s *[[Social media]] activism *[[Strike action]]s |result=<!--fill when conflict is over, status should be empty--> *'''Arizona''': 20 percent pay raise<ref>{{cite web|last1=Snow|first1=Anita|last2=Tang|first2=Terry|title=Arizona teachers end walkout after governor signs off on 20 percent raise|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-arizona-teacher-protests-20180503-story.html|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[tronc]]|accessdate=May 3, 2018|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> *'''Colorado''': 2 percent pay raise; increased school spending<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whaley|first1=Monte|title=Pueblo teachers reach tentative agreement with district for 2 percent pay hike|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/05/12/pueblo-teacher-strike-is-over/|website=[[The Denver Post]]|publisher=[[Digital First Media]]|accessdate=May 13, 2018|date=May 12, 2018}}</ref> *'''Oklahoma''': Increased school funding, teacher raises by $6,000, support staff raises by $1,250<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2018/04/teachers-strikes-oklahoma-socialism-sanders-unions|title=Red Oklahoma|last=Blanc|first=Eric|date=13 April 2018|publisher=Jacobin|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/us/oklahoma-teachers-strike.html|title=Oklahoma Teachers End Walkout After Winning Raises and Additional Funding|last=Goldstein|first=Dana|date=12 April 2018|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> *'''West Virginia''': 5 percent pay raise<ref name="krieg">{{cite news|last1=Krieg|first1=Gregory|title=Is the West Virginia teachers' strike the future of American labor?|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/05/politics/west-virginia-teachers-strike-future-unions/index.html|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=6 March 2018|publisher=CNN}}</ref> |howmany1= * ~20,000 in Arizona * ~6,000 in Colorado * ~2,000 in North Carolina * ~10,000 in Oklahoma * ~10,000 in West Virginia |howmany2= | leadfigures1 = * [[American Federation of Teachers]] * [[Democratic Socialists of America]] * [[Industrial Workers of the World]] * [[National Education Association]] * State education associations | leadfigures2 = * [[Government of Arizona]] * [[Government of Colorado]] * [[Government of North Carolina]] * [[Government of Oklahoma]] * [[Government of West Virginia]] |fatalities= |injuries= |arrests= }}
The '''2018 education workers' strikes in the United States''' began on February 22, 2018, after local activists dragged the West Virginia state leadership of the West Virginia branches of the American Federation of Teachers and the National Education Association into holding a strike vote. The strike—which ended when teachers returned to their classrooms on March 7—inspired similar, statewide strikes in [[2018 Oklahoma teachers' strike|Oklahoma]] and [[2018 Arizona teachers' strike|Arizona]]. It also inspired smaller-scale protests by school staff in Kentucky, North Carolina, Colorado, and led to a [[2018 DeKalb County School District bus drivers' strike|school bus driver strike]] in Georgia. Additionally, around this time, [[adjunct professors]] at [[Virginia Commonwealth University]] in Richmond, Virginia [[VCUarts adjunct workers' protests|protested over pay]].
Motivations for the strikes include low wages for teachers and support staff, inadequate school budgets, overcrowded classrooms, and other problems. The strikes varied in their levels of success, with West Virginia considered mostly successful, where Oklahoman teachers received relatively few concessions.
==Origins and overview== {{update|date=June 2018}} Discussions of a strike in West Virginia began in early 2018. In the first week of February, teachers staged "walk-ins" at schools and some protested at the West Virginia Capitol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/371989-hundreds-of-teachers-hold-walkout-protest-in-west-virgina|title=Hundreds of teachers hold walkout, protest in West Virginia|last=Delk|first=Josh|date=2 February 2018|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> The strike proved successful, and inspired those in other states to strike as well.<ref name="Rios Mother Jones">{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2018/03/educators-across-the-us-are-using-west-virginias-teachers-strike-to-inspire-their-own-battle-plans/|title=Educators Across the US Are Using the West Virginia Teachers’ Strike to Inspire Their Own Battle Plans – Mother Jones|last=Rios|first=Edwin|date=23 March 2018|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|publisher=Mother Jones|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>
In early April, Oklahoma became the [[2018 Oklahoma teachers' strike|second state to strike]], making it the first time a teacher's strike was held in the state since 1990.<ref name=intercept>{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/03/06/oklahoma-teacher-strike-west-virginia/|title=TEACHER UNREST SPREADS TO OKLAHOMA, WHERE EDUCATORS ARE “DESPERATE FOR A SOLUTION”|last=Cohen|first=Rachel|date=March 6, 2018|publisher=The Intercept|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> The strike lasted for 10 days, from April 2-12, after teacher salaries were increased by $6,000 and support staff salaries were increased by $1,250.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/04/arizona-teachers-vote-statewide-strike-180420075924512.html|title=US: Arizona teachers vote for first-ever statewide strike|date=April 20, 2018|publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref>
In late April, teachers in Arizona and in Colorado went on strike. The [[2018 Colorado teachers' strike|Colorado strike]] began on April 27<ref>{{cite web|title=Schools in Arizona and Colorado set to stay closed due to teacher strike|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-arizona-education/schools-in-arizona-and-colorado-set-to-stay-closed-due-to-teacher-strike-idUSKBN1I11MJ|website=[[Reuters]]|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|accessdate=April 30, 2018|date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> and ended on May 12.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pueblo teachers reach tentative agreement with district for 2 percent pay hike|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/05/12/pueblo-teacher-strike-is-over|website=[[Denver Post]]|accessdate=November 30, 2018|date=May 12, 2018}}</ref>, while the [[2018 Arizona teachers' strike|Arizona Strike]] lasted from April 26 to May 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Snow |first1=Anita |last2=Tang |first2=Terry |title=Arizona teachers end walkout after governor signs off on 20 percent raise |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-arizona-teacher-protests-20180503-story.html |website=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>
In May 2018, it was reported that teachers in North Carolina could be next to strike, making it the fifth state to have a teachers' strike.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elk|first1=Mike|title=North Carolina Teachers to Strike in May – Louisiana Teachers Could Follow – Georgia Bus Drivers Fired for Striking|url=http://paydayreport.com/north-carolina-teachers-to-strike-in-may-louisiana-teachers-could-follow-georgia-bus-drivers-fired-for-striking/|website=paydayreport.com|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> This was due to the state being ranked 41st in the nation in salaries for teachers, and per pupil spending at negative 12 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scott|first1=Tamara|title=Report: North Carolina ranks 37th in nation for teacher pay|url=http://www.wnct.com/news/local-news/a-new-report-suggests-north-carolina-could-be-the-next-state-to-see-teacher-strikes/1151839964|website=[[WNCT-TV]]|publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> Further, it was reported that teachers in North Carolina have seen a five percent decrease in salaries since 2008. Furthermore, teachers hired after January 1, 2021, will not receive health benefits, along with teachers having to pay $10,000 per year in out of pocket health insurance.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strauss|first1=Valerie|title=Could North Carolina’s teachers be next to strike? Here’s the mess they’re in.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/answer-sheet/wp/2018/05/01/could-north-carolinas-teachers-be-next-to-strike-heres-the-mess-theyre-in/|website=washingtonpost.com|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=May 1, 2018}}</ref>
Because of a majority of the strikes being in predominantly Republican Party-controlled, conservative states,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carlson|first1=Deven|title=Not just a ‘red-state revolt’: The story behind the Oklahoma teacher walkout|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/brown-center-chalkboard/2018/04/12/oklahoma-teacher-walkouts-backstory/|website=brookings.edu|publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> the strikes have been referred to as the "Red State Revolt".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pearce|first1=Matt|title=Red-state revolt continues: Teachers strike in Oklahoma and protest in Kentucky|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-teachers-spending-20180402-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[tronc]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Weir|first1=Bill|title=Arizona teachers walk out of their poorly equipped classrooms|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/26/us/arizona-teacher-walkout-weir/index.html|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jamieson|first1=Dave|last2=Waldron|first2=Travis|title=The Red-State Teacher Revolt Has Been Brewing For Decades|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/americas-growing-teacher-strikes-were-decades-in-the-making_us_5ac8f468e4b0337ad1e8979c|website=[[HuffPost]]|publisher=[[Oath Inc.]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> This has prompted several Republican politicians to concede to their demands, in the run-up to the [[United States elections, 2018|2018 mid-term elections]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Teacher rebellion puts red-state Republicans on defensive|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-oklahoma-teacher-strike-20180403-story.html|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=[[tronc]]|accessdate=May 2, 2018|date=April 3, 2018}}</ref>
===Demands===
Universally, demands included raising pay.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://splinternews.com/oklahoma-is-the-latest-red-state-where-teachers-are-ris-1824260223|title=Oklahoma Is the Latest Red State Where Teachers Are Rising Up|last=Osberg|first=Molly|date=2 April 2018|publisher=Splinter|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://arizonaeducatorsunited.com/demands|title=We demand...|publisher=AEU|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> In Oklahoma and West Virginia, respectively sources of [[Oil in Oklahoma|oil]] and [[Economy_of_West_Virginia#Energy|coal]], demands included financing the increased spending on education through taxation focused on these industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/147266/west-virginia-teachers-strike-takes-aim-coal-gas|title=The West Virginia Teachers’ Strike Takes Aim at Coal and Gas|last=Jones|first=Sarah|date=2 March 2018|publisher=The New Republic|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2018/04/oklahoma-teacher-strike-education-funding|title=The Oklahoma Strike Is At a Crossroads|last=Blanc|first=Eric|date=11 April 2018|publisher=Jacobin|accessdate=29 April 2018}}</ref>
