'''Erich P. Schwandt''' (born 1935 in [[Paso Robles]], [[California]] – 2 August 2017 in [[Victoria (British Columbia)|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/timescolonist/obituary.aspx?pid=186643634|title=Erich P. Schwandt: Obituary|journal=Victoria Times Colonist|publisher=Legacy.com|date=13 September 2017|accessdate= 26 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>) was a Canadian [[cembalist]], [[organist]], [[musicologist]] and music educator.
Schwandt studied [[harpsichord]] with [[Putnam Aldrich]] and gave harpsichord and organ concerts on [[CBC/Radio-Canada|CBC]], throughout Canada and the USA. He taught music history and musicology at the [[Stanford University]] and the [[Eastman School of Music]]. His particular academic interest was the relationship between music and dance in the 17th and 18th centuries, and he published articles in publications such as ''[[Musical Quarterly]]'', ''Notes'', ''Fontes Artis Musicae'', ''Canadian University Music Review'' and ''The New Grove''. He created more than a dozen music editions and reconstructed the ''Gloria'' from Erik Satie's ''[[Messe des pauvres]]'' for a performance at the [[University of Victoria]] in 1997.
