{{BLP unsourced|date=October 2017}} {{primary sources|date=October 2017}} '''Peter Alan Cundall''' is an engineer who invented the [[Discrete Element Method]]. He is the founder of Itasca Consulting Group.
He studied for a [[PhD]] in [[Rock Mechanics]] at [[Imperial College London]], graduating in 1971 with a thesis titled "The measurement and analysis of accelerations in rock slopes".<ref>[http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.320411 Cundall, P. A. (1971) The measurement and analysis of accelerations in rock slopes. PhD thesis. Imperial College London]</ref> In 1979 he published "A discrete numerical model for granular assemblies",<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Cundall| first1 = Peter A. | title = A discrete numerical model for granular assemblies | doi = 10.1680/geot.1979.29.1.47 | journal = Géotechnique | volume = 29 | issue = 1 | pages = 47–65 | year = 1979 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> which the most-widely cited paper in the journal [[Géotechnique]], and which set the ground for the development of the DEM method. He served as Faculty member at the [[University of Minnesota]] for some time and then he went on to form Itasca Consulting Group.
