'''Suzette Haden Elgin''' (born '''Patricia Anne Wilkins'''; November 18, 1936 – January 27, 2015) was an American science fiction author and linguist. She founded the [[Science Fiction Poetry Association]] and is considered an important figure in the field of science fiction [[constructed language]]s. Her best-known non-fiction includes the ''[[Verbal self defense|Gentle Art of Verbal Self-Defense]]'' series.

==Life==
Patricia Anne Wilkins was born in 1936 in [[Jefferson City, Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clute|first=John|authorlink=John Clute|title=Suzette Haden Elgin|work=Science Fiction Encyclopedia|publisher=Gollancz|year=2012|url=http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/elgin_suzette_haden|accessdate=2012-04-16}}</ref>

She attended the [[University of California, San Diego]] (UCSD) in the 1960s, and began writing science fiction in order to pay tuition. She gained a PhD in [[linguistics]], and was the first UCSD student ever to write two dissertations (on English and [[Navajo language|Navajo]]).

She created the [[engineered language]] [[Láadan]] for her ''[[Native Tongue (Suzette Haden Elgin novel)|Native Tongue]]'' science fiction series.<ref>{{cite news|first=Amy|last=Chozick|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/12/arts/television/in-game-of-thrones-a-language-to-make-the-world-feel-real.html|title=Athhilezar? Watch Your Fantasy World Language|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 11, 2011}}</ref> A grammar and dictionary was published in 1985. She supported [[feminist science fiction]], saying "women need to realize that SF is the only [[genre]] of literature in which it's possible for a writer to explore the question of what this world would be like if you could get rid of [Y], where [Y] is filled in with any of the multitude of real world facts that constrain and oppress women. Women need to treasure and support science fiction."<ref>{{cite web|last=Wells|first=Kim|title=An Interview with Suzette Haden Elgin|work=Women Writers.net|year=1999|url=http://www.womenwriters.net/editorials/hadenelgin.htm|accessdate=2012-04-16}}</ref>

In addition, she published works of shorter fiction. Overlying themes in her work include [[feminism]], [[linguistics]] and the impact of proper [[language]], and peaceful coexistence with nature. Many of her works also draw from her [[Ozark]] background and heritage.<ref>[http://ozarque.livejournal.com/profile Elgin blog], ozarque.livejournal.com; accessed April 26, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.sfwa.org/members/elgin/index.html#Biography Elgin biography], sfwa.org; accessed April 26, 2015.</ref>

==Later years and death==
Elgin became a professor at [[San Diego State University]] (SDSU). She retired in 1980 and lived in [[Arkansas]] with her second husband, George Elgin. She died at age 78 in 2015 from undisclosed causes. She was survived by her husband. Her son Michael pre-deceased her.<ref>[https://www.sfsite.com/news/2015/01/28/obituary-suzette-haden-elgin notice of death opg Suzette Haden Elgin], SFSite News; accessed April 26, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.locusmag.com/News/2015/02/suzette-haden-elgin-1936-2015 Locus Online obituary], locusmag.com; accessed April 26, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://ozarque.livejournal.com/631306.html], 7th draft of her poem about Michael's death.</ref>

